Add a new niri action called `FitWorkspaceColumns` that takes all tiling columns on the current workspace and sets each to equal proportional width so they collectively fill the display without scrolling.

## Files to modify (in order):

### 1. `niri-ipc/src/lib.rs`
Add `FitWorkspaceColumns {}` variant to the `Action` enum, right after `ExpandColumnToAvailableWidth {}`. Doc comment: "Set all columns on the workspace to equal width, fitting them to the display."

### 2. `niri-config/src/binds.rs`
- Add `FitWorkspaceColumns` variant to the config `Action` enum (around line 324, after `ExpandColumnToAvailableWidth`)
- Add the `From<niri_ipc::Action>` conversion (around line 627, after the ExpandColumnToAvailableWidth line): `niri_ipc::Action::FitWorkspaceColumns {} => Self::FitWorkspaceColumns,`

### 3. `src/layout/scrolling.rs`
Add a `pub fn fit_workspace_columns(&mut self)` method on `ScrollingSpace<W>`, right after `expand_column_to_available_width` (around line 2835). The logic:

```rust
pub fn fit_workspace_columns(&mut self) {
    let col_count = self.columns.len();
    if col_count <= 1 {
        return;
    }

    let proportion = 1.0 / col_count as f64;

    for col in &mut self.columns {
        col.is_full_width = false;
        col.is_pending_maximized = false;
        col.preset_width_idx = None;
        col.width = ColumnWidth::Proportion(proportion);
        col.update_tile_sizes(true);
    }

    cancel_resize_for_columns(&mut self.interactive_resize, &self.columns);

    // Update cached column data widths
    self.update_data();

    // Scroll view to show the first column
    self.animate_view_offset_to_column(None, self.active_column_idx, None);
}
```

IMPORTANT: Look at how `update_data` works and how `cancel_resize_for_columns` or equivalent works. If `cancel_resize_for_columns` doesn't exist, just set `self.interactive_resize = None;`. Also check if `update_data()` exists - it might be something else that recalculates `self.data` (the cached `ColumnData` widths). Search for how `self.data` entries get their `width` field updated. It might happen inside `update_tile_sizes` or there might be a separate method. Look at what other methods do after changing column widths.

Actually, `ColumnData.width` might be updated automatically. Check how `set_column_width` or `toggle_full_width` handle the data cache. If `data` is updated lazily or via some other mechanism, you may not need to call `update_data()`.

